, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"nl":{"about 1075–1142":"circa 1075–1142","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1075–1142":"1075–1142","1075–1139":"1075–1139","1102–1193":"1102–1193","1105–1213":"1105–1213","1044–1096":"1044–1096","1046–Female":"1046–Overleden","about 1096":"circa 1096","1044":"1044","1142":"1142","1075":"1075","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1193":"1193","1060":"1060","1139":"1139","1105":"1105","1213":"1213","1102":"1102","1046":"1046","about 1075":"circa 1075","Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Colombières, , Basse-Normandie, France":"Colombières, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk","Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1075–1142":"about 1075–1142","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1075–1142":"1075–1142","1075–1139":"1075–1139","1102–1193":"1102–1193","1105–1213":"1105–1213","1044–1096":"1044–1096","1046–Female":"1046–Deceased","about 1096":"about 1096","1044":"1044","1142":"1142","1075":"1075","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1193":"1193","1060":"1060","1139":"1139","1105":"1105","1213":"1213","1102":"1102","1046":"1046","about 1075":"about 1075","Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Colombières, , Basse-Normandie, France":"Colombières, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","France":"France","Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Giffard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: (i) relationship name from the Continental Germanic personal name  <i>Gifard</i>. (ii) nickname, perhaps sometimes from Old French  <i>giffard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffords","meanings":["English: variant of   Gifford  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jefford","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]},{"name":"Guiver","meanings":["English: (i) nickname, apparently from Middle English  <i>giver</i> ‘giver, donor, bestower’. (ii) variant of   Giffard   with voicing of /f/ to /v/ and loss of final  <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Gafford","meanings":["English (southeastern): assimilated form of <b>Gatford</b>, a name of various origins. In Sussex and Surrey it is perhaps a variant of the habitational name <b>Catford</b> from a place so called in Somerset. <b>Gatford</b> is also from the habitational names Gateford (in Worksop, Nottinghamshire) or Gateforth (near Selby, Yorkshire), both formed with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, influenced by Old Norse <i>geit</i> ‘goat’.","Probably also an altered form of German <b>Gaffert</b>: habitational name from Gaffert near Köslin, Brandenburg, or from a personal name formed with Middle High German <i>gate</i> ‘fellow, companion’. The surname <i>Gaffert</i> is very rare in Germany.","English: perhaps an altered form of   Gatewood  , an occupational name for a ‘goatherd’ (Middle English <i>gate-werde</i>, Old English <i>gātweard</i>) or for a ‘gate keeper’ (Middle English <i>gateward</i>, Old English <i>ʒeatweard</i>, dialect <i>gātward</i>)."]},{"name":"Gifford","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."]},{"name":"Jefferd","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Giffard was born about 1075, in Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales, her father, Lord Osborne de Giffard II  Lord of Brimpsfield, was 33 and her mother, Weva de Crepon, was 31. She married Roger de Chandos III. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1142, in Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 68."},"et":{"about 1075–1142":"umbes 1075–1142","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1075–1142":"1075–1142","1075–1139":"1075–1139","1102–1193":"1102–1193","1105–1213":"1105–1213","1044–1096":"1044–1096","1046–Female":"1046–Surnud","about 1096":"umbes 1096","1044":"1044","1142":"1142","1075":"1075","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1193":"1193","1060":"1060","1139":"1139","1105":"1105","1213":"1213","1102":"1102","1046":"1046","about 1075":"umbes 1075","Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Colombières, , Basse-Normandie, France":"Colombières, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa","Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1075–1142":"noin 1075–1142","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1075–1142":"1075–1142","1075–1139":"1075–1139","1102–1193":"1102–1193","1105–1213":"1105–1213","1044–1096":"1044–1096","1046–Female":"1046–Kuollut","about 1096":"noin 1096","1044":"1044","1142":"1142","1075":"1075","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1193":"1193","1060":"1060","1139":"1139","1105":"1105","1213":"1213","1102":"1102","1046":"1046","about 1075":"noin 1075","Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Colombières, , Basse-Normandie, France":"Colombières, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, Ranska","France":"Ranska","Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Goldcliff, Monmouthshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1075–1142":"environ 1075–1142","1060–1130":"1060–1130","1075–1142":"1075–1142","1075–1139":"1075–1139","1102–1193":"1102–1193","1105–1213":"1105–1213","1044–1096":"1044–1096","1046–Female":"1046–Décédée","about 1096":"environ 1096","1044":"